Certainly! You can add a confirmation box to a delete button using the `window.confirm` method in JavaScript. Here's an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
</head>
<body>

  <button onclick="confirmDelete()">Delete</button>

  <script>
    function confirmDelete() {
      // Display a confirmation dialog
      var isConfirmed = window.confirm("Are you sure you want to delete?");

      // Check if the user confirmed
      if (isConfirmed) {
        // If confirmed, perform the delete action
        alert("Deleted!"); // Replace this with your actual delete logic
      } else {
        // If not confirmed, do nothing or provide feedback
        alert("Deletion canceled.");
      }
    }
  </script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, when the "Delete" button is clicked, a confirmation dialog will appear. If the user clicks "OK," it will show an alert indicating that the deletion was confirmed. If the user clicks "Cancel," it will show an alert indicating that the deletion was canceled. Replace the `alert("Deleted!");` line with your actual delete logic.